excerpt: Renaissance mansion housing paintings & prints by Francisco de Goya, plus other Spanish artists.
detail_description: The Goya Museum, located in a Renaissance mansion, showcases an impressive collection of paintings and prints by Francisco de Goya along with works by other Spanish artists. The museum's exhibition is centered around the Aragonese painter's work, featuring 14 paintings, a drawing, and the complete series of Goya's engravings. Visitors can also explore author-themed museums such as the Pablo Gargallo Museum and the IAACC Pablo Serrano to experience different artistic styles.
name: Goya Museum
address: C. de Espoz y Mina, 23, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: UNESCO-listed 11th-century palace now used as seat of the Aragonese Parliament, with guided tours.
detail_description: Aljafería Palace, also known as Palacio de la Aljaferia, is a must-visit in Zaragoza. This 11th-century palace serves as the seat of the Aragonese Parliament and offers guided tours. The palace's fortified exterior contrasts with its stunning interior featuring Mudejar art declared a UNESCO World Heritage site. Inside, visitors can admire the breathtaking myrhab, alveolate arches, an orange tree patio, and the golden hall.
name: Aljafería Palace
address: C. de los Diputados, s/n, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: When exploring Zaragoza, a must-visit is the Mercado Central de Zaragoza, a vibrant marketplace that has been at the heart of the city since its opening in 1903. This stunning structure showcases beautiful iron and glass architecture typical of the 19th century, creating an inviting atmosphere for visitors. Inside, you'll be greeted by a sensory feast—an array of fresh produce bursting with color, along with regional delicacies like meats, cheeses, and fish.
name: Mercado Central de Zaragoza
address: Av. de César Augusto, 110, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Original artworks from 20th century Spanish sculptor Pablo Gargallo in a Renaissance-style palace.
detail_description: The Pablo Gargallo Museum, located in the historic Old Town district of Zaragoza, is dedicated to showcasing the remarkable sculptures of 20th-century Spanish artist Pablo Gargallo. Housed in the Renaissance-style Argillo Palace, this museum offers a glimpse into the mastery of Gargallo's avant-garde art. Visitors can also explore temporary exhibitions and year-round events at this cultural venue.
name: Pablo Gargallo Museum
address: Pl. de S. Felipe, 3, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Large city park with botanical gardens, sculptures & fountains plus cafes & bicycle rentals.
detail_description: Parque Grande José Antonio Labordeta is a sprawling city park in Zaragoza, offering a serene escape from urban life. It features botanical gardens, sculptures, and fountains, as well as amenities like cafes and bicycle rentals. The park spans over 40 hectares and boasts around 15 fountains, a botanic garden, viewpoints, terraces, paths, statues, and even a swimming pool for the summer months.
name: Parque Grande José Antonio Labordeta
address: Parque Grande de José Antonio Labordeta, s/n, 50006 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: 1908 museum dedicated to archaeology & fine art, with Roman & Islamic artefacts & paintings by Goya.
detail_description: The Zaragoza Museum, established in 1908, is a treasure trove of archaeology and fine art. It houses an impressive collection of Roman and Islamic artifacts as well as captivating paintings by the renowned artist Goya. The museum offers a rich cultural experience with its diverse exhibition rooms and monuments. One can explore archaeological items from the province of Zaragoza and a significant Goya collection among other pieces.
name: Zaragoza Museum
address: Pl. de los Sitios, 6, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Elaborate courtyard from a 1550s merchant's house with friezes, columns, arches & balconies.
detail_description: Fundación Ibercaja Patio de la Infanta is a captivating 16th-century Renaissance courtyard nestled in the heart of Zaragoza. Originally part of a merchant's house, it was later transformed into a private residence for the Aragonese Infanta Catherine of Austria. The courtyard boasts stunning architectural features such as friezes, columns, arches, and balconies that showcase the city's rich history.
name: Fundación Ibercaja Patio de la Infanta
address: C. de San Ignacio de Loyola, 16, 50008 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Sala de Exposiciones La Lonja, located in Zaragoza, Spain, is a stunning example of Renaissance architecture influenced by Florentine and Mudejar styles. Built between 1541 and 1551 as the city's commercial exchange center, it has since become the most important exhibition space in Zaragoza. This historical landmark showcases the best art exhibitions from around the world and is considered one of the finest examples of Aragonese-Renaissance design.
name: Sala de Exposiciones La Lonja
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, s/n, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Zaragoza is the capital of northeastern Spain's Aragon region. Overlooking the Ebro River in the city center is baroque Nuestra Señora del Pilar basilica, a famous pilgrimage site with a shrine to the Virgin Mary and multiple domes. Mudéjar-style landmarks, combining Islamic and Gothic architecture, include the Aljafería, an 11th-century Moorish palace, and the Cathedral of the Savior, begun in the 12th century.
detail_description: Zaragoza, the capital of Spain's Aragon region, is a charming city with a mix of architectural styles. The Nuestra Señora del Pilar basilica, overlooking the Ebro River, is a famous pilgrimage site with stunning baroque design. The city also boasts Mudéjar-style landmarks like the Aljafería palace and the Cathedral of the Savior. Despite its beauty, some visitors have noted an unpleasant smell in certain areas.
name: Zaragoza
address: Spain

excerpt: Stately 15th-century stone bridge spanning the Ebro River, known for imposing stone lion statues.
detail_description: The Stone Bridge Zaragoza, also known as Puente de Piedra, is a historic 15th-century bridge that spans the Ebro River and serves as an iconic landmark in the city. Adorned with imposing stone lion statues, this picturesque bridge offers stunning views of Zaragoza and the river, making it a popular destination for both locals and tourists. Visitors can take leisurely strolls across the bridge, capturing photographs of the scenic surroundings.
name: Stone Bridge
address: Puente de Piedra, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

name: Monumento "la Cruz de Piedra del Puente de Piedra" en Zaragoza
address: Puente de Piedra, Casco Antiguo, 50014 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Multimedia museum around archaeological remains of a Roman forum from the time of Emperor Augustus.
detail_description: The Museo del Foro de Caesaraugusta, located in Zaragoza, Spain, is a captivating museum dedicated to the ancient Roman forum of Caesaraugusta. This multimedia museum offers visitors a chance to explore the archaeological remains of the forum, which was once the political, social, and economic center of the Roman city. As you wander through the museum, you can walk along recreated streets of the forum and see depictions of shops and vendors from that era.
name: Museo del Foro de Caesaraugusta
address: Pl. de la Seo, 2, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Pedestrian-only central road lined with stately, 19th-century homes.
detail_description: C. de Alfonso I is a charming pedestrian-only street in the historic center of Zaragoza, lined with elegant 19th-century homes and an array of shops. Walking down this picturesque street offers stunning views of the towering basilica and the ornate balconies that adorn the buildings. Along the way, visitors can explore quaint storefronts, stop at local cafes on Placa Sas, and even visit historic passages like Ciclon.
name: C. de Alfonso I
address: Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Archeological remains of a 1st-century AD Roman arena at the city's highest point, revealed in 1972.
detail_description: The Museo del Teatro de Caesaraugusta in Zaragoza offers a captivating journey into the city's Roman history. It features the archaeological remains of a 1st-century AD Roman arena, uncovered in 1972. The museum showcases the ancient Roman theater, once accommodating 6,000 spectators. Visitors can enjoy panoramic views of the excavation process from the ground floor and explore audiovisual presentations and 3D models depicting its former grandeur in the basement.
name: Museo del Teatro de Caesaraugusta
address: C. de San Jorge, 12, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: Located at Plaza Nuestra Senora del Pilar in Zaragoza, the Fuente de la Hispanidad is a remarkable fountain built in 1991 to commemorate Christopher Columbus's discovery of the Americas. Designed by sculptor Francisco Rallo Lahoz, it features a central figure of Columbus surrounded by sculptures representing indigenous cultures from the Americas. The fountain's unique shape resembles that of Latin America when viewed from above, with water cascading down its facade to represent the northern coast of the continent.
name: Fuente de la Hispanidad
address: Pl. de Ntra. Sra. del Pilar, 1, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Art shows, screenings & talks in a geometric concrete & aluminium structure designed by Carme Pinós.
detail_description: Located in Zaragoza, CaixaForum Zaragoza is a modern cultural center housed in a striking geometric concrete and aluminum structure designed by Carme Pinós. The venue offers a diverse range of exhibitions, screenings, and talks suitable for all ages. Visitors can immerse themselves in international culture through art, fashion, photography, and film exhibits and workshops. In addition to its cultural offerings, the center's avant-garde building itself is an intriguing modern architectural attraction.
name: CaixaForum Zaragoza
address: Av. de José Anselmo Clavé, 4, Delicias, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Historic church, founded in the 13th century, with Gothic & Moorish architectural elements.
detail_description: The Parish Church of San Pablo, also known as Iglesia de San Pablo, is a historic church in Zaragoza with a rich heritage dating back to the 13th century. It features a captivating blend of Gothic and Moorish architectural styles. Situated in the traditional San Pablo neighborhood, it holds significant cultural and religious importance as the third most important Catholic Church in Saragossa city.
name: Parish Church of San Pablo
address: C. de San Pablo, 42, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: El Balcón del Tubo is a vibrant district located in the heart of Zaragoza's historic center, known for its bustling atmosphere, quality tapas, and lively nightlife. The area is lined with numerous bars and restaurants nestled within narrow streets. Surrounding this district are notable historical landmarks such as the Goya Museum, Caesaraugusta Roman Theatre Museum, Pilar Tower, and Basilica Nuestra Senora del Pilar along the banks of River Ebro.
name: El Balcón del Tubo
address: C. de los Estébanes, 7, Casco Antiguo, 50003 Zaragoza, Spain

excerpt: Contemporary works by local & international painters & sculptors in an eye-catching building.
detail_description: IAACC Pablo Serrano, also known as the Aragonese Institute of Contemporary Art and Culture, is a striking building that houses an impressive collection of modern art. Located in Zaragoza, it serves as a hub for contemporary culture, offering not only visual arts but also dance, music, and literature.
name: IAACC Pablo Serrano
address: P.º de María Agustín, 20, Casco Antiguo, 50004 Zaragoza, Spain

detail_description: The Iglesia Parroquial de la Seo, also known as the Cathedral of El Salvador, is a significant religious site in Zaragoza. It stands as the second cathedral in the city and was constructed between 1681 and 1872. This historical landmark holds great importance to the Catholic church, being linked to the first-ever church dedicated to Mary dating back to 40 AD. The interior features a small chapel dedicated to Saint Michael with a stunning Mudejar wall and roof.
name: Iglesia Parroquial de la Seo
address: Pl. de la Seo, 4, Casco Antiguo, 50001 Zaragoza, Spain
